reviewText: Full of Life is one of my favorites by Judy Holliday, a wonderful family story with some drama but gentle humor. Judy and her husband, played by Richard Conte, are expecting their first child. Add to this nervous time a house with termites and an Italian father-in-law who (thinks he) knows best. It's a sweet and happy contrast with Judy's other family drama, "The Marrying Kind" which has far less humor and much more drama and even tragedy. "Full of Life" is full of love and joy.

reviewText: A delightful, genuinely heartwarming comedy, starring Judy Holliday and Richard Conte as a young couple about to have a child, yet still struggling to define what their family life will mean to them, and Salvatore Baccaloni as Conte's broadly portrayed Italian Papa.  Fans of Judy Holliday will love this film -- she leaves her "dumb blonde" character aside in favor of a much richer role; she gets some great comedic moments in early on, acting out the clumsiness and moodiness of late-term pregnancy, yet also portrays a smart, intuitive young woman who provides the rational and emotional glue which holds her family together.  There are a lot of subtle touches to this film; nothing is overplayed or hackneyed, and although it is set in the white-picket fence era of the early '50s, the issues addressed in the script will ring true for many viewers for decades to come.  Recommended!
